PECAN PIPELINE COMPANY STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
VERSION 0.1.0
EFFECTIVE MARCH 20, 2025
eTariff Information Tariff Submitter: Pecan Pipeline Company FERC Tariff Program Name: FERC NGPA Gas Tariff Tariff Title: NGPA 311 Section 311 Service Tariff Record Proposed Effective Date: March 20, 2025 Tariff Record Title: NGPA Section 311, Statement of Operating Conditions Option Code: A -2-

1 INTRODUCTION Pecan Pipeline Company (Transporter) is an intrastate pipeline, with Transporters facilities located wholly within the State of Texas, and is exempt from the jurisdiction of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) under the Natural Gas Act of 1938 (NGA). Transporter is a gas utility under Texas law and provides intrastate Gas service subject to the jurisdiction of the Railroad Commission of Texas (Intrastate Service). Transporter is also an intrastate pipeline within the meaning of Section 2(16) of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978 (NGPA) and provides interstate services pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA, as implemented by Subpart C of Part 284 of the regulations of FERC (Section 311 and Section 311 Service). This Statement of Operating Conditions (SOC) provides the general terms and conditions under which Transporter will provide Services to qualified customers pursuant to Section 311. If by providing Service pursuant to these regulations, Transporters status as a pipeline that is exempt from NGA jurisdiction is impacted, altered, or threatened in any way, then Transporter reserves the right to terminate all such Section 311 Service and all Service Agreements related thereto, and to withdraw this SOC. Unless otherwise indicated in its Service Agreement, Customer shall have no contractual remedy, and Transporter shall have no liability, for Services related to periods subsequent to the termination of Section 311 Service. The rules and regulations of FERC govern all Section 311 Service. If any term or provision in the Service Agreement is inconsistent with these rules or regulations or this SOC, the rules, regulations and this SOC will control, and the Service Agreement will be deemed modified accordingly. 2 DEFINITIONS Except as otherwise specified, the following terms as used herein and in the Service Agreement will be construed to have the following scope and meaning: 2.1 Adequate Assurance of Performance is defined in Section 13.9.3 of this SOC. 2.2 Anchor Customer means a Customer that has provided the revenue support for the Pipeline System as it existed on the In-Service Date pursuant to an intrastate Service Agreement for Firm Service that has a term of twenty (20) Contract Years or longer. 2.3 Applicable Law means any act, order, code, rule or regulation of any court or Governmental Authority or agency with proper jurisdiction, domestic or foreign, applicable to a Service Agreement or the activities thereunder, as same may be amended and in force from time to time. 2.4 Btu means British thermal unit, which is the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one pound of water from 59 degrees Fahrenheit to 60 degrees Fahrenheit. 2.5 CCT means Central Clock Time and is defined as current time in the Central Time Zone taking into consideration the seasonal changes back and forth between Daylight Savings and Standard Time. 2.6 CO2 means carbon dioxide. 2.7 Compression Fee is the fee the Parties agree upon for Compression Service in the Service Agreement, which shall be consistent with the Statement of Rates. 2.8 Compression Service means the provision of natural gas compression, including the pressurization of natural gas to facilitate its transportation, delivery, or injection into a Pipeline System, and the operation, maintenance, and utilization of compression equipment necessary to achieve the required pressure levels as specified by Transporter. 2.9 Condensate means hydrocarbons that have condensed from the Gas downstream of the Receipt Point(s) and are collected as a liquid in Transporters facilities at or upstream of the Delivery Point(s). 2.10 Confirmation means an effective and unexpired agreement documented by written means evidencing an affirmative agreement between Transporter and Customer on all key terms and conditions for a particular Nomination under a Service Agreement; Customers submission of a Nomination without an affirmative agreement by Transporter to all terms of service does not constitute a Confirmation. 2.11 Contract Year means the period commencing on the Effective Date and ending on the first anniversary of the Effective Date, unless otherwise specified in a Service Agreement, and each successive twelve (12)-month period thereafter during the Term of a Service Agreement; provided, however, that if the Term ends prior to the completion of a full twelve (12)-month period, the final Contract Year shall be deemed to end on the termination date of the Service Agreement. 2.12 Creditworthiness Requirements means the measures of creditworthiness or Adequate Assurance of Performance set forth in Section 13.9 that Transporter requires as a condition for the provision of the Services. 2.13 Customer is the Party for which Transporter provides Services under this SOC. 2.14 Day means the period beginning at 9:00 a.m. CCT on each calendar day and ending at 9:00 a.m. on the following calendar day. 2.15 Dehydration Fee is the fee the Parties agree upon for Dehydration Service in the Service Agreement, which shall be consistent with the Statement of Rates. 2.16 Dehydration Service means, for any Gas received from Customer with water vapor in excess of the maximum amount provided for in the Quality Specifications, Transporters treating service to reduce such water vapor content to the level required by such Quality Specifications. 2.17 Delivery Point(s) means the point(s) at which Gas is delivered by Transporter to Customer. 2.18 Dispute is defined in Section 12.9.1 of this SOC. 2.19 Dispute Notice is defined in Section 12.9.1 of this SOC. 2.20 Effective Date means the first Day of the term of a Service Agreement. 2.21 Equivalent Quantity is defined in Section 5.1 of this SOC. 2.22 Excess Quantities is defined in Section 6.2 of this SOC. 2.23 FERC is defined in Section 1 of this SOC and includes any successor agency. 2.24 Firm or Firm Service means that the capacity used to provide the service is not subject to a prior claim by another Customer or another class of service and receives the priority of service as set forth in Section 5. 2.25 Force Majeure is defined in Section 13.6.2 of this SOC. 2.26 Fuel means Lost and Unaccounted for Gas and Pipeline System fuel. 2.27 Gas or gas means any mixture of gaseous hydrocarbons and other gases (including carbon dioxide), in a gaseous state, consisting primarily of methane. 2.28 Gas Daily Average Price means the price published in Platts Gas Daily Price Guide® (as published by S&P Global) under the heading Daily Midpoint Averages for East Texas for Houston Ship Channel for such applicable Month. 2.29 Governmental Authority means any court or tribunal in any jurisdiction (foreign or domestic) or any federal, state, municipal, local, or foreign government or other governmental body, agency, authority (including any state attorneys general office or office of consumer protection), department, commission, board, bureau, instrumentality, arbitrator or arbitral body (domestic or foreign), with proper jurisdiction, including FERC. 2.30 Greenhouse Gas, or GHG means certain components that may from time to time comprise part of the Gas, consisting of water vapor, carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone, or has such meaning as otherwise defined by Applicable Law. 2.31 Gross Heating Value means the number of Btu liberated by the complete combustion, at constant pressure, of one cubic foot of Gas at a base temperature of 60 degrees Fahrenheit and a referenced pressure base of 14.73 psig with air of the same temperature and pressure of the Gas, after products of combustion are cooled to the initial temperature of the Gas, and after the water of the combustion is condensed to the liquid state. Transporter shall correct the Gross Heating Value of the Gas for the water vapor content of Gas being delivered, but if the water vapor content of the Gas is seven (7) pounds or less per 1,000,000 cubic feet, then the Gas is deemed to be dry and no correction is to be made. 2.32 Imbalance means any difference between the Equivalent Quantity and the actual quantity of Gas redelivered under the Service Agreement in any one (1) Month as calculated on an MMBtu basis. 2.33 Impacted Location is defined in Section 5.2 of this SOC. 2.34 Indemnified Parties is defined in Section 13.5.4 of this SOC. 2.35 Indemnifying Party is defined in Section 13.5.4 of this SOC. 2.36 In-Service Date means October 6, 2023 for Intrastate Service and March 20, 2025 for Section 311 Service, as applicable. 2.37 Interruptible or Interruptible Service means that the capacity used to provide the Transportation Service is not Firm, is subject to a prior claim by another Customer or another class of service, and receives a lower priority than such other Customer or class of service as set forth in Section 5. 2.38 Intrastate Service is defined in Section 1 of this SOC. 2.39 Loss means any actual loss, cost, expense, liability, encumbrance, damage, demand, suit, sanction, claim, cause of action, judgment, lien, fine, or penalty, including court costs and reasonable attorneys fees and costs of investigation and defense. 2.40 Lost and Unaccounted for Gas means the quantity of Gas, expressed in MMBtu, that is released or lost through piping, equipment, operations, measurement losses, or inaccuracies to the extent not adjusted pursuant to measurement procedures in this SOC or a Service Agreement, or is vented, flared, or otherwise lost in connection with the operation of the Pipeline System. 2.41 Maximum Daily Delivery Obligation or MDDO means the maximum daily delivery obligation at any Primary Delivery Point or Secondary Delivery Point, as set forth in the Service Agreement. 2.42 Maximum Daily Quantity or MDQ means the maximum quantity of Gas in MMBtu, exclusive of applicable Retention Quantities, that Customer may nominate and deliver each Day for Firm Service at a Receipt Point(s) or an aggregate of Receipt Points at a relatively uniform hourly rate over the course of such Day, as specified in a Confirmation. 2.43 Maximum Daily Receipt Obligation or MDRO means the maximum daily receipt obligation at any Primary Receipt Point or Secondary Receipt Point, as set forth in the Service Agreement. 2.44 Maximum Hourly Quantity is defined in Section 6.3 of this SOC. 2.45 MMBtu means 1,000,000 Btus. 2.46 MMcf means 1,000,000 cubic feet. 2.47 Month means a period of time beginning at 9:00 a.m. CCT on the first Day of a calendar month and ending at 9:00 a.m. CCT on the first Day of the following calendar month. 2.48 NGA is defined in Section 1 of this SOC. 2.49 NGPA is defined in Section 1 of this SOC. 2.50 Nomination means the quantity of Gas in MMBtu Customer expects to make available and deliver at each Receipt Point each Day, or portion thereof, and receive at each Delivery Point each Day, or portion thereof. 2.51 OBA is defined in Section 8.3.5 of this SOC. 2.52 Operational Flow Order is defined in Section 8.4.1 of this SOC. 2.53 Part 284 Regulations is defined in Section 13.1.1 of this SOC. 2.54 Party or Parties refers to the Customer and/or Transporter, as applicable. 2.55 Person means any individual, partnership, limited partnership, joint venture, corporation, limited liability company, estate, custodian, trustee, executor, administrator, nominee, representative, unincorporated organization, sole proprietorship, trust, employee benefit plan, Governmental Authority or other entity. 2.56 Pipeline System means the 36-inch diameter pipeline and related equipment that Transporter will construct, own, and operate to receive, dehydrate, treat, compress, transport and deliver Customers Gas from the Receipt Point(s) to the Delivery Point(s) identified in the applicable Service Agreement. 2.57 Primary Delivery Point means those Delivery Point(s) on the Pipeline System listed in a Service Agreement with a specified Firm MDDO, as may be amended upon mutual agreement from time to time. 2.58 Primary Firm Service means Firm Service which is scheduled from a Primary Receipt Point at or below the respective point MDRO to a Primary Delivery Point which is at or below its respective point MDDO. 2.59 Primary Point means a Primary Delivery Point and/or a Primary Receipt Point, as applicable. 2.60 Primary Receipt Point means those Receipt Point(s) on the Pipeline System listed in a Service Agreement with a specified Firm MDRO, as may be amended upon mutual agreement from time to time. 2.61 Psig means pounds per square inch gauge. 2.62 Quality Specifications is defined in Section 13.3.1 of this SOC. 2.63 Receipt Point(s) means the point(s) at which Gas is received by Transporter from Customer. 2.64 Renegotiation Notice is defined in Section 13.3.6(a) of this SOC. 2.65 Retention Quantities means a Customers allocated share of the quantity of any Gas that is actually retained by Transporter for Fuel. 2.66 Scheduled Quantity means the quantity of Gas up to the MDQ, plus any applicable Retention Quantities, nominated by a Customer and scheduled by Transporter. 2.67 Secondary Delivery Point means any Delivery Point on the Pipeline System that is listed as a Secondary Delivery Point under a Service Agreement for use on an as-available basis. 2.68 Secondary Firm Service means Firm Service which is scheduled from a Secondary Receipt Point and/or to a Secondary Delivery Point. 2.69 Secondary Point means a Secondary Delivery Point and/or a Secondary Receipt Point, as applicable. 2.70 Secondary Receipt Point means any Receipt Point on the Pipeline System that is listed as a Secondary Receipt Point under a Service Agreement for use on an as-available basis. 2.71 Section 311 is defined in Section 1 of this SOC. 2.72 Section 311 Service is defined in Section 1 of this SOC. 2.73 Service Agreement means the agreement and all related exhibits between Transporter and Customer for Services. 2.74 Service Fees are the fees the Parties agree upon for Services in the Service Agreement, which shall be consistent with the Statement of Rates. 2.75 Services means any service provided by Transporter to Customer hereunder, including Transportation Service, Compression Service, Dehydration Service and Treating Service. 2.76 SOC is defined in Section 1 of this SOC. 2.77 Statement of Rates means the Statement of Rates attached hereto as Exhibit A. 2.78 Taxes means gross production, severance, conservation, ad valorem, and similar or other taxes measured by or based upon production, together with all taxes on the right or privilege of ownership of Gas, or upon the handling, transmission, compression, processing, treating, conditioning, distribution, sale, use, delivery, or redelivery of Gas, including all of the foregoing now existing or in the future imposed or promulgated. 2.79 Tax Indemnifying Party is defined in Section 13.5.6 of this SOC. 2.80 Term is defined in Section 10.1 of this SOC. 2.81 Termination Notice is defined in Section 13.3.6(a) of this SOC. 2.82 Thermal Content means with respect to Gas, the product of (i) a volume of Gas and (ii) the Gross Heating Value of such Gas, adjusted to a same pressure base of 14.73 psig, as expressed in MMBtus; and with respect to Condensate, the product of (x) a volume of Condensate and (y) the Gross Heating Value of such Condensate. 2.83 Transportation Fee means the fees the Parties agree upon for Transportation Service in the Service Agreement, which shall be consistent with the Statement of Rates. 2.84 Transportation Service means the receipt, compression, transportation and delivery of Gas from the Receipt Point(s) to the Delivery Point(s) nominated by Customer. 2.85 Transporter is defined in Section 1 of this SOC. 2.86 Treating Fee is the fee the Parties agree upon for Treating Service in the Service Agreement, which shall be consistent with the Statement of Rates. 2.87 Treating Service means, for any Gas received from Customer with CO2 in excess of the maximum amount provided for in the Quality Specifications, Transporters treating service to reduce such CO2 to the level required by such Quality Specifications. 3 SERVICES 3.1 Eligibility of Customer; Request for Service. 3.1.1 To be eligible for Section 311 Service, Customer must represent and warrant to Transporter that the requested Transportation Service complies with the requirements of Section 311. 3.1.2 If, subsequent to commencement of the Section 311 Service, Transporter in its reasonable discretion has reason to question the validity of Customers representation and warranty that the requested Transportation Service complies with the requirements of Section 311, Transporter may refuse to accept Customers tendered deliveries and may continue refusal until Customer satisfies Transporter, in its reasonable discretion, of such representation and warranty. 3.1.3 Customer must meet the Creditworthiness Requirements in Section 13.9. 3.1.4 In order to enter into a Service Agreement, Customer shall request Transportation Service in writing. Customer must execute a Service Agreement prior to receiving Transportation Service. 3.1.5 Each request for Transportation Service will include the following information: (a) Customer - the exact legal name and type of entity; mailing and street address; and the name, address and telephone number of primary contact for Customer regarding the transportation arrangement. (b) MDQ - The requested MDQ (stated in MMBtu/Day). (c) Term of Service - the date Transportation Service is requested to commence and the date Transportation Service is requested to terminate. (d) Receipt and Delivery Point(s) - The Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s) for all Gas tendered to Transporter for transportation under the Service Agreement. (e) Eligibility Information sufficient for Transporter to confirm that the requested Transportation Service would comply with the requirements of Section 311. 3.2 Firm Service. Subject to the terms of this SOC and the applicable Service Agreement, Transporter will provide Firm Service on its Pipeline System for each Firm Service Customer. With respect to each daily Nomination of Gas for Firm Service under a Service Agreement, Customer may nominate a quantity of Gas not to exceed its MDQ. Transporter shall not contract for Firm Services with any other party if the Firm Services under such additional Service Agreement will result in Transporter being unable to provide Firm Service to existing Firm Service Customers during the Term of their Service Agreements. Nominations and receipts at the Receipt Points over and above the allocated Firm Service MDQ will be made on an Interruptible Service basis. 3.3 Interruptible Service. Subject to the terms of this SOC and the applicable Service Agreement, Transporter will provide Interruptible Service on its Pipeline System for Customer on an as-available, Interruptible Service basis. For Interruptible Service, Transporter will not be obligated to receive, transport, or re-deliver any minimum quantity of Gas. 3.4 Discounts. Transporter and Customer may mutually agree upon a discounted rate that varies from the maximum rate established in the Statement of Rates. 3.5 Intrastate Service. In addition to Section 311 Service, Transporter performs Intrastate Service. To provide Customer with flexibility to access intrastate and/or interstate markets, Customer may contract for both Intrastate and Section 311 Service on mutually agreeable terms, and Transporter will, at Customers option, administer Customers Intrastate and Section 311 Service Agreements on an integrated basis such that Customers combined usage under the Intrastate and Section 311 Service Agreements cannot exceed the MDQ indicated per Section 8 of Customers Service Agreement; provided, however, that Transporters provision of Section 311 Service, without undue discrimination, shall not be conditioned on Customers subscription to intrastate capacity. The description of available Intrastate Services contained herein is provided for informational purposes only and shall not be construed to make such Intrastate Service subject to FERC regulation. 3.6 Service Agreement. A Service Agreement is required for all Services hereunder and will be subject to all terms and provisions of this SOC and Customers Service Agreement. 4 OPERATING CONDITIONS 4.1 In carrying out its Day-to-Day operations, Transporter, in its reasonable discretion, will determine the manner in which the Pipeline System will be utilized and which Transportation Service or requested Transportation Service will be provided. Transporter agrees to operate and maintain the Pipeline System and all equipment utilized to provide the Services hereunder as a prudent operator and in compliance with applicable regulations. 4.2 Transporter will not be required to provide Transportation Service if Transporter reasonably believes that the provision of such Transportation Service is precluded due to emergency or would result in unsafe operating conditions. 4.3 Transporter will not be required to provide Transportation Service if all facilities necessary to effectuate the Transportation Service are not in existence when the request for Transportation Service is made. 4.4 Transporters maximum obligation and minimum obligation to accept and redeliver Gas will be specified in the Service Agreement. 4.5 Transporter will not be required to perform Transportation Service on behalf of Customer if Customer is in breach of this SOC or the Service Agreement. 5 CUSTOMER AND TRANSPORTER OBLIGATIONS; CURTAILMENT 5.1 Obligations of Transporter. Transporter agrees to receive all Gas at the Receipt Point(s) up to the Scheduled Quantity as nominated and tendered by Customer under the terms of this SOC and any applicable Service Agreement, transport the Gas and deliver thermally-equivalent quantities of Gas, in MMBtu, to Customer at the Delivery Point(s), equivalent to the aggregate quantity of Gas received from Customer at all of the Receipt Point(s), less the Retention Quantities as set forth in Section 9.5 of this SOC (Equivalent Quantity). Such contractual rights to receive, transport, and deliver Gas to the Delivery Point(s) are subject to: (i) an event of Force Majeure; (ii) Customers failure or refusal to deliver Gas to or receive Gas as required under this SOC, Customers Service Agreement, or Applicable Law; (iii) any Applicable Law which limits, prevents, or interferes with Transporter performance; (iv) the requirements of downstream pipelines; provided, however, that such requirements are beyond Transporters reasonable control, and which, despite Transporters exercise of due diligence, Transporter is unable to deliver the Equivalent Quantity; and (v) as otherwise provided under any other terms and conditions in this SOC or any applicable Service Agreement. Customer acknowledges that the quantity of Gas physically received or delivered may be different than the Scheduled Quantity. In the event of constraints at a Delivery Point(s) or on a downstream pipeline, Transporter will rely on the downstream partys allocation at the affected Delivery Point(s) and, to the extent Customers Nominations are reduced, Customer will be deemed to have failed to receive Gas as required hereunder. 5.2 Interruption of Service. If, for whatever reason, Transporter does not have sufficient capacity available to accommodate all Nominations through specific Receipt Point(s), specific Delivery Point(s), and/or specific segments of the Pipeline System (the Impacted Location), Transporter, with respect to the Services provided pursuant to and governed by this SOC, will interrupt the applicable Service in accordance with the following schedule of priorities, beginning with the first Transportation Service to be interrupted and continuing in order as necessary to the last Transportation Service to be interrupted: 5.2.1 Interruptible Service; 5.2.2 Secondary Firm Service; 5.2.3 Primary Firm Service; provided, however, that, upon any curtailment event, Firm Service that is Intrastate Service shall be scheduled as set forth in 16 Texas Administrative Code § 7.455. 5.3 Within priority 5.2.1 and priority 5.2.2 above, interruption will be administered on the basis of price, with the Customer paying the maximum rate receiving the highest priority. All remaining capacity shall be allocated such that the Customer paying the next highest rate per MMBtu will receive the next highest priority. If two or more Interruptible Service or Secondary Firm Service customers are paying the same rate for Section 311 Service, interruption will be administered on a pro rata basis based upon each Customers nomination. Within priority 5.2.3 above, capacity will be allocated pro rata based on each Customers MDQ as applicable so that each Customer incurs an equal percentage reduction of its transportation rights. To clarify, all lower priority service levels shall be fully curtailed before Primary Firm Service is allocated; all Interruptible Service shall be fully curtailed before Secondary Firm Service is allocated. 5.4 Notwithstanding the foregoing, should any third party with the right to control the Receipt Point(s), Delivery Point(s), or any other facilities needed for Transporter to perform such Services limit or fail to authorize the use of any such facilities, Transporter shall have no obligation hereunder to perform any Services affected by such limitation or failure. 5.5 Curtailment Liability. Transporter shall not be liable for any loss or damage to any Person or property caused, in whole or in part, by any curtailment of service, except to the extent caused solely by Transporters gross negligence or willful misconduct. Customer agrees to indemnify Transporter from and against any and all claims resulting from, arising out of, or in any way related to a curtailment of Customers service, regardless of cause (but not to the extent caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of Transporter). 5.6 Customers Obligations. Customer will tender the Scheduled Quantity at the Receipt Point(s), and accept such Gas, less the Retention Quantities, at the Delivery Point(s). Customers obligations set forth in the preceding sentence are subject to: (i) an event of Force Majeure; (ii) Transporters failure or refusal to receive Gas from, or deliver Gas to, Customer as required under this SOC and any applicable Service Agreement; (iii) any Applicable Law which limits, prevents, or interferes with Customers performance; and (iv) as otherwise provided under any other terms and conditions in this SOC and any applicable Service Agreement. 6 QUANTITY 6.1 Quantity. Customers MDQ is as set forth in the Service Agreement. Subject to the terms, conditions, and limitations contained herein, Customer, or Customers designee, agrees to deliver, or cause to be delivered, to the Receipt Point(s), and Transporter agrees that it will accept those daily quantities of Gas scheduled in accordance with Section 5.1 of this SOC and tendered daily at the Receipt Point(s). Subject to the terms, conditions, and limitations contained herein, Customer agrees on any Day to accept, or cause to be accepted, at the Delivery Point(s), and Transporter agrees that it will transport and deliver at the Delivery Point(s), all Gas received from Customer at the Receipt Point(s) regardless of the Scheduled Quantity for such Day, subject to (i) Section 7 of this SOC, (ii) Transporter curtailment procedures, (iii) the provisions of any Operational Flow Order (copies of which will be promptly communicated to Customer in accordance with Section 8.4.1) and (iv) Force Majeure. 6.2 If Customer has quantities of Gas available on any Day for delivery to Transporter in excess of the MDQ (Excess Quantities), Customer may tender such Excess Quantities for delivery to Transporter, and Transporter may in each such instance, accept or refuse delivery of all or any part of such Excess Quantities. Any Excess Quantities so accepted by Transporter will be transported on an Interruptible basis and subject to all of the terms and provisions of the SOC. 6.3 Maximum and Minimum Delivery and Receipt Quantities. The maximum quantity of Gas that Transporter is obligated to receive hereunder at the Receipt Point(s) and deliver hereunder at the Delivery Point(s) during any given hour of any Day is 1/24th of Customers Scheduled Quantity at an instantaneous standard volumetric flow rate at any point in time during the hour (the Maximum Hourly Quantity), unless otherwise specifically provided in the Service Agreement. Transporter has no obligation to receive, transport, and deliver quantities of Gas hereunder in excess of Customers MDQ. Transporter has no obligation to receive or deliver Gas in quantities exceeding the physical capacity of the Delivery Points or Receipt Points. 6.4 Maximum Daily Receipt and Delivery Obligation. 6.4.1 Up to two (2) times each Contract Year (or such additional times as the Parties may mutually agree in writing) during the Term of the Service Agreement, and upon no less than thirty (30) Days prior written notice, Anchor Customer may allocate up to one hundred twenty-five percent (125%) of the MDQ, in any combination, amongst the Receipt Point(s), provided that Anchor Customers allocation at any Receipt Point shall not exceed the physical meter capacity of the Receipt Point, with such allocation to be in place unless and until Anchor Customer again reallocates its MDQ amongst the Receipt Points in accordance with this Section 6.4.1. In addition, (i) if there is a change in the Receipt Point meter size or (ii) if there is a change in Anchor Customers MDQ, then Anchor Customer may again reallocate its MDQ amongst the Receipt Points on the first Day after the applicable change, subject to availability. For the avoidance of doubt, this Section 6.4.1 is limited to point MDQ reallocation and is not intended to give Customer the right to tender for Transportation Service more than its MDQ. 6.4.2 Customer shall allocate its MDQ amongst the Delivery Point(s) as provided in the Service Agreement. In no event shall Customer have the right to transport a quantity on the Pipeline System on any Day in excess of the MDQ on a Firm Service basis. For Anchor Customer, up to two (2) times each Contract Year during the Term of the Service Agreement (or such additional times as the Parties may mutually agree in writing), and upon no less than thirty (30) Days prior written notice, Anchor Customer may reallocate up to one hundred twenty-five percent (125%) of its MDQ (in the aggregate between all applicable Service Agreements, in any combination), amongst the Delivery Points, subject to available capacity, depending on Anchor Customers written election, with such allocation to be in place unless and until Customer again reallocates its MDQ amongst Delivery Point(s) in accordance with this Section 6.4.2. If, during the Term or any term extension agreed to in the applicable Service Agreement, the capacity at any Delivery Point(s) should become unavailable due to maintenance or Force Majeure, Anchor Customer may reallocate up to one hundred twenty-five percent (125%) of its MDQ (in the aggregate between all applicable Service Agreements, in any combination) amongst the unaffected Delivery Point(s) upon no less than one (1) Days prior written notice, subject to available capacity at each such Delivery Point, provided, however, that Anchor Customer will always have the right to transport a quantity of Gas on the Pipeline System on any day up to the MDQ. Upon Transporters notification to Anchor Customer of the conclusion of any such Force Majeure event, Anchor Customers MDDO allocation shall revert to the allocation in effect immediately prior to Anchor Customers modification in response to the Force Majeure event on either the second Business Day following Transporters notification of the cessation of the Force Majeure event or the next Day following such notification, based on Anchor Customers election provided in writing to Transporter. Nominations and deliveries at any Delivery Point over and above the allocated Firm Service MDQ or under the Firm Service MDQ but over the MDDO will be made on an Interruptible Service basis. In addition, if there is a change in Quality Specifications as provided in Section 13.3.5 herein, then Anchor Customer may again reallocate its MDQ amongst the Delivery Points on the first Day after the applicable change, subject to availability. For the avoidance of doubt, this Section 6.4.2 is limited to point MDQ reallocation and is not intended to give Customer the right, in aggregate, to Transportation Service for more than its MDQ. 6.5 All Quantities in MMBtu. All quantities of Gas received and delivered under any Service Agreement will be expressed in terms of MMBtu, including, without limitation, calculation of payments, determination of Imbalances, and determination of Retention Quantities. 6.6 Pipeline Capacity Expansion. Anchor Customer shall have a right of first refusal to obtain additional Firm Service capacity from Transporter above Anchor Customers then-applicable MDQ as a result of (a) any expansion by Transporter of the Pipeline System capacity, or (b) any extension of the Pipeline System to an additional delivery point. 6.7 Interconnections. Transporter shall not provide an interconnection to any third party for Transportation Service on the Pipeline System unless there is (a) unsubscribed capacity available on the Pipeline System; and (b) such third party is similarly situated to Customer with respect to Customers commitments under the Service Agreement and SOC. 7 RECEIPT POINT(S) AND DELIVERY POINT(S) 7.1 Receipt Point(s). Customer and Transporter shall tender and/or receive (as applicable) Gas at the Receipt Point(s) under this SOC and Customers Service Agreement. Transporter shall operate, maintain and repair all facilities necessary to provide Transportation Service from the Receipt Point(s) and at Transporters sole cost and expense. 7.2 Delivery Point(s). Transporter shall deliver Gas to Customer or its agent under this SOC and the applicable Service Agreement. Transporter shall operate, maintain and repair all facilities necessary to provide Transportation Service to the Delivery Point(s) and at Transporters sole cost and expense. 7.3 Pressure at Receipt Point(s). Customer (or its designee) will deliver Gas at the Receipt Point(s) at pressures sufficient to enter the Pipeline System at such points, but Customers delivery pressure into the Pipeline System at the Receipt Point(s) may not exceed Transporters maximum allowable operating pressure, as such may vary from time to time, at any such point or cause the pressure at any such point to exceed Transporters maximum allowable operating pressure. Unless otherwise provided in an applicable Service Agreement, Transporter shall have no obligation to alter its pipeline pressures, provide compression, or modify its pipeline operations in order to effectuate the receipt or delivery of Gas. In the event Transporter anticipates that the operating pressure will exceed the target operating pressure, Transporter shall promptly notify Customer of same, in writing, along with all measures being taken by Transporter to reduce the operating pressure at the affected Receipt Point(s) to a level at or below the target operating pressure. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in the event the operating pressure exceeds the target operating pressure for more than six (6) hours in any twenty-four (24) hour period, then Transporter shall provide Customer a credit against the Transportation Fee in the amount of $0.04 per Mcf for all volumes delivered by Customer during the pressure exceedance. 7.4 Pressure at Delivery Point(s). Transporter will deliver Customers Gas at operating pressure specified for the Delivery Point(s), as such may vary from time to time. 8 NOMINATIONS AND BALANCING 8.1 Nominations. All nominations for Transportation Service will be submitted by Customer or its agent to Transporter at least Monthly, but as frequently as daily if desired, via instant message or email or through such other electronic or written means as Transporter will specify, in accordance with Transporters standard nomination procedures, as amended from time to time. Transporter will send Customer a Confirmation for each Nomination. Each party warrants that, at all times during the term of any applicable Service Agreements, it will commit no action or omission that will cause the service provided to Customer, to fail to comply with all Applicable Law, including the on behalf of provisions of the Part 284 Regulations. 13.2 MEASUREMENT Customers Gas will be measured in accordance with the provisions of this Section 13.2. 13.2.1 Facilities. Transporter or Transporters designee, will maintain and operate the metering facilities to measure the quantities of Gas delivered at each of the Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s) in accordance with the terms of the SOC. Transporter or Transporters designee, will determine the Thermal Content of the Gas by the facilities at the Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s). Such facilities and measurement data with respect to the Gas covered hereby shall at all reasonable times be subject to inspection by Customer. Customer may, at its own expense, install, maintain, and operate check measuring equipment of standard make using separate taps at the Receipt Point(s) in accordance with the standards set forth in Section 13.2.4. Check meters shall not interfere with operation of Transporters equipment. Transporter will have access to Customers check measuring equipment at all reasonable hours, but only Customer will calibrate, adjust, operate, and maintain the check measuring equipment. 13.2.2 Unit of Measurement. (a) The unit of measurement for the purpose of receipt and delivery of natural gas is one MMBtu. (b) The unit of volume for the purpose of measurement is one Mcf at a pressure of 14.73 psig and at a temperature of 60 degrees Fahrenheit and the measuring Party shall compute the readings and registrations of the metering equipment into such unit of volumes as well as MMBtus. 13.2.3 Pressure. Atmospheric pressure is assumed to be 14.73 psig. 13.2.4 Standards. The measuring Party shall compute all orifice meter quantities in accordance with the American Gas Association (AGA) Measurement Committee Report No. 3 and the American National Standards Institute / American Petroleum Institute (ANSI/API) 2530-1985 or the latest edition as agreed to by Customer and Transporter (herein referred to as AGA 3). The measuring Party shall compute all turbine meter quantities in accordance with AGA Measurement Committee Report No. 7, Measurement of Natural Gas by Turbine Meter, 2006. The measuring Party shall compute all ultrasonic meter quantities in accordance with AGA Measurement Committee Report No. 9, Measurement of Gas by Multipath Ultrasonic Meters, 2007. The measuring Party shall correct all meter quantities for deviations from the ideal gas laws (super compressibility) in accordance with AGAs Transmission Measurement Committee Report No. 8, dated November 1992, or the latest edition. The actual method employed will be mutually agreed by Customer and Transporter. 13.2.5 Method. The measuring Party shall determine the Gross Heating Value, the specific gravity, and the chemistry of the Gas by use of on-line chromatography as follows: GPA 2145 Physical Constants for Paraffin Hydrocarbons and Other Components of Natural Gas, as amended, GPA 2261 Analysis for Natural Gas and Similar Gaseous Mixtures by Gas Chromatography, as amended, GPA 2172 Calculation of Gross Heating Value, Relative Density, and Compressibility of Natural Gas Mixtures from Compositional Analysis, as amended will be utilized in the calculations. The measuring Party shall incorporate Gas quality into the original flow calculations in the flow computer at periods mutually agreed by Customer and Transporter. Customer and Transporter shall have the option of witnessing the calibrations and calculations performed within the chromatograph. The measuring Party shall operate all chromatographs on a C6+ basis, with the assumed physical properties for the C6+ component to be mutually agreed upon by the Parties. Other components to be quantified include C1, C2, C3, IC4, NC4, IC5, NC5, NeoC5, N2, and CO2. The measuring Party shall perform all calculations for heating value and specific gravity on a normalized basis. Unnormalized total shall not deviate from one hundred percent (100%) by more than two percent (2%) unless Transporter agrees to operate from time to time outside this tolerance. 13.2.6 Pulsation. Customer shall have the right to conduct such pulsation tests on its own facilities as it deems prudent, at its sole risk and expense. If excessive pulsation is evident, mutually agreed modifications to operation or facility design will be made to reduce the effect of such pulsation. If pulsation issues cannot be resolved in a mutually agreeable manner, then either Party shall have the right to refuse delivery or receipt of Gas. 13.2.7 Orifice Meter Tubes. Each Party shall make all of its orifice meter tubes available for inspection prior to installation and at those times when cleaning is performed. All meter tubes must conform to the restrictions of AGA 3, or later editions as agreed by Customer and Transporter. 13.2.8 Electronic Flow Measurement. If electronic flow measurement is used, then the differential and pressure determining instruments shall have a stated accuracy not to exceed 0.1% of full scale and shall not have a static pressure effect exceeding 0.2% per 1,000 Psig. 13.2.9 Meter Proving. All meters must conform to applicable AGA reports and will be calibrated/proven on a schedule, but in no event will the calibration period be in excess of ninety (90) Days. The measuring Party shall provide notification of scheduled calibrations to all interested parties and shall make reasonable efforts to accommodate respective schedules, but calibration will proceed at the scheduled time regardless of attendees. 13.2.10 Corrections. If, after testing, a meter is found to be inaccurate by any amount exceeding one percent (1%) at a reading corresponding to the average hourly rate of flow for the period since the last preceding test, then the measuring Party shall correct any previous reading of such equipment to zero error for any period of inaccurate reading which is known or definitely agreed upon, but in the case the period is not known or agreed upon, for a period extending over one-half (1/2) of the time elapsed since the last test, not exceeding a correction period of forty-five (45) Days. 13.2.11 Calibration. The measuring Party shall use a calibration standard of a type and class that is shown by the manufacturers specifications to be twice as accurate as the instrument being calibrated. The measuring Party shall certify all differential and pressure standards once per year to conform to the manufacturers stated accuracy by a National Institute of Standards and Technology traceable standard. 13.2.12 Estimation. If any meter was left out of service or is found to be registering inaccurately, then the measuring Party shall determine the quantities of Gas delivered by: (a) correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, tests, or mathematical calculations; (b) using the registration of any check equipment, if installed and accurately registering; or (c) estimating the quantity or quality of Gas by the quantity or quality of Gas during the preceding periods under similar conditions provided the equipment was registering accurately at that time. 13.3 QUALITY 13.3.1 Quality Specifications. Customer represents and warrants that all Gas tendered for transportation at the Receipt Point(s) is merchantable Gas and, for each constituent, meets the more stringent of (x) the quality specifications required for the acceptance of Gas by any downstream pipeline located at a Delivery Point, or (y) the quality specifications set forth below (or as modified from time to time or as set out in any applicable Service Agreement) (the Quality Specifications): (a) Be commercially free of soap, grease, dust, gum, gum-forming constituents, and other solid or liquid matter that can be removed with dehydrators and ordinary field separators; (b) Contain not more than one-fourth (¼) grain of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) cubic feet; (c) Contain not more than one-half (1/2) grain of total sulfur per one hundred (100) cubic feet; (d) Contain not more than two percent (2%) by volume of CO2; (e) Contain not more than two percent (2%) by volume of nitrogen as an aggregate blended stream; (f) Contain not more than ten (10) parts per million by volume of oxygen; (g) Contain not more than three percent (3%) by volume of non-hydrocarbon gases as an aggregate blended stream; (h) Contain not more than seven (7) pounds of water vapor per MMcf at any Receipt Point; (i) Contain a minimum of 950 Btu as an aggregate blended stream; (j) Contain a maximum of 1,100 Btu as an aggregate blended stream; and (k) Have a temperature of not more than one hundred twenty degrees Fahrenheit (120°F), nor less than forty degrees Fahrenheit (40°F). 13.3.2 Disposal of Liquids. Transporter shall have the right to gather and dispose of all liquids and Condensate in the Pipeline System and retain any proceeds in connection therewith. 13.3.3 Odorizing. Upon request from Transporter, Customer shall provide documentation acceptable to Transporter demonstrating that Customer has made such contractual arrangements for such off-specification Gas on the path for which Customer has nominated Gas. This provision should not be construed as a general waiver to any specification and is only available where physical blending, treatment, and/or conditioning of Gas is contracted for and will take place prior to reaching the downstream pipeline whose specifications are to be met and such acceptance and service by Transporter shall not adversely impact markets on the Pipeline System. Acceptance of Gas that does not conform to the Quality Specifications does not constitute a waiver of the Quality Specifications with respect to such Gas, any other Gas delivered under a Service Agreement in the future, or any claim for damages due to such failure to conform, unless Transporter knew of the non-conforming nature of such Gas but continued to receive such Gas, after a reasonable period of time in which to suspend receipt. 13.3.5 New Quality Specifications. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Transporter may from time to time, revise the SOC so that the Quality Specifications conform to the specifications of receiving pipelines downstream of the Delivery Point(s). In such event, Transporter shall provide as much advance notice as is commercially practical to Customer, in writing, of the proposed changes prior to the effectiveness thereof. 13.3.6 Greenhouse Gas Emissions. Transporter shall provide such auditors as Customer may designate with reasonable access to Transporters premises solely for the purpose of performing audits or inspections permitted hereunder. Customer shall obligate such auditors to protect the confidentiality of and restrict the use of all confidential information to performing the audit contemplated herein. Transporter shall provide such reasonable audit assistance described above at no charge for one (1) audit per calendar year, but Customer shall bear all costs and expenses in connection with any audit hereunder. Transporter shall reply in writing to an audit report within ninety (90) Days after receipt of such report. If Customer and Transporter fail or are unable to resolve any audit disputes, then the Parties shall resolve the matter using the dispute resolution procedures set forth in Section 12.9.1 of the SOC. (b) Terms of Access. Customer shall conduct all on-site monitoring and other audits and inspections by auditors and inspectors employed or retained by Customer pursuant to this Section 13.4.4 in such a manner so as not to interfere with the normal operations of Transporter. While on the premises of Transporter, Customer shall ensure that auditing personnel observe the rules and requirements of Transporter regarding security and personal or professional conduct and appearance. (c) Cessation of Audit Rights. Customer will have up to twenty-four (24) Months after the close of a calendar year in which to make an audit of Transporter records, as applicable, for such calendar year. Notwithstanding the foregoing, all rights of access and audit provided hereunder terminate twenty-four (24) Months after the expiration of the term of the Service Agreement. 13.5 WARRANTIES, LIABILITY, AND INDEMNIFICATIONS 13.5.1 Title. Customer warrants that it owns or has the right to control all Gas delivered by it hereunder and that it has the right to deliver the same hereunder and that such Gas is free from liens, encumbrances, and adverse claims of every kind. Customer hereby agrees to indemnify, defend, and hold harmless Transporter from and against any and all Losses (including Losses of Transporter related to any SOC) arising out of or related to any breach of the foregoing representation and warranty. Customer shall at all times have title to or right to possess all Gas received and delivered hereunder. 13.5.2 Jurisdiction. Customer represents and warrants to Transporter: (a) (i) in the event the Customer does not specify, when submitting its nomination, that Gas is destined for NGPA Section 311 Service then Customer represents and warrants that such Gas will be produced in the State of Texas from reserves not dedicated or committed to interstate commerce, and (ii) that the Gas which Customer delivers or receives hereunder will not have been or be sold, consumed, received and redelivered or otherwise utilized in interstate commerce at any point upstream of the Receipt Point(s) or downstream of the Delivery Point(s), nor have been or be commingled at any point upstream of the Receipt Point(s) or downstream of the Delivery Point(s) with other Gas which is or may be sold, consumed, received and redelivered or otherwise utilized in interstate commerce in such a manner which will subject Transporter to regulation as a natural gas company by FERC or any successor authority under Sections 4, 5 or 7 of the Natural Gas Act. Customer agrees to indemnify and hold Transporter harmless from and against any and all suits, actions, damages, costs, losses and expenses sustained by Transporter relative to any breach by Customer of the covenants herein expressed; or (b) in the event Customer specifies, when submitting its nomination, that Gas originates from, or that is destined to be sold, dedicated, committed to or delivered in, interstate commerce, whether immediately upstream or downstream of Transporter or ultimately, Customer represents and warrants that such Gas shall be eligible for transportation in interstate commerce under applicable rules, regulations, or orders of FERC and that the service which it requests qualifies as a bona fide transportation service under NGPA Section 311 and the related rules and will continue to qualify under such section for the entire term of the Service Agreement and shall be subject to all valid rules and regulations of duly constituted Governmental Authorities having jurisdiction or control over the matter related hereto including, without limitation, the provisions of the Part 284 Regulations implementing NGPA Section 311 (18 C.F.R. § 284.121, et seq). Transporter shall then make arrangements, utilizing its rights under the SOC(s), to receive Gas from the Receipt Point(s) and redeliver to the Delivery Point(s) in such a manner as to be in compliance with NGPA Section 311. 13.5.3 Additional Warranties. Each Party represents that: (i) it has all necessary power and authority to execute, deliver, and perform its obligations under this SOC and any applicable Service Agreement; (ii) the execution, delivery, and performance by it of this SOC and any applicable Service Agreement and the consummation of the transactions contemplated thereby have been duly authorized by all necessary actions, including corporate, partnership, and shareholder action; (iii) each of this SOC and each applicable Service Agreement has been duly executed and delivered and constitutes its legal, valid, and binding obligation enforceable in accordance with its terms; and (iv) the execution, delivery, and performance by it of this SOC and each applicable Service Agreement and the consummation of the transactions contemplated thereby do not violate any Applicable Law or its constitutive documents or violate or result in a default under any agreement or instrument binding on it or any of its subsidiaries or assets. 13.5.4 Indemnification; Responsibility for Injury or Damage. As between the Customer on the one hand, and Transporter on the other hand: (i) Customer is deemed to be in exclusive control and possession of the Gas and responsible for any injury or damage relating to handling, gathering, transportation, delivery, and receipt of Gas upstream of the Receipt Point(s) and at and downstream of the Delivery Point(s); and (ii) Transporter is deemed to be in exclusive control and possession and responsible for any injury or damage relating to handling, transporting, receipt, and delivery of Gas at and downstream of the Receipt Point(s) and upstream of the Delivery Point(s). THE PARTY HAVING, OR DEEMED TO HAVE, CONTROL AND POSSESSION OF GAS UNDER THE PRECEDING SENTENCE (THE INDEMNIFYING PARTY) SHALL RELEASE, DEFEND, INDEMNIFY, AND HOLD THE OTHER PARTY, ITS AFFILIATES, AND ITS AND THEIR RESPECTIVE SHAREHOLDERS, MEMBERS, OFFICERS, DIRECTORS, EMPLOYEES, AND AGENTS (COLLECTIVELY, THE INDEMNIFIED PARTIES) HARMLESS FROM AND AGAINST ALL LOSSES ARISING FROM ACTUAL AND ALLEGED BODILY INJURY, DEATH, AND PROPERTY DAMAGE RELATING TO GAS WHILE SUCH GAS IS IN THE INDEMNIFYING PARTYS CONTROL AND POSSESSION; PROVIDED, HOWEVER, AN INDEMNIFYING PARTY IS NOT OBLIGATED TO RELEASE, DEFEND, INDEMNIFY, OR HOLD ANY INDEMNIFIED PARTY HARMLESS TO THE EXTENT OF SUCH INDEMNIFIED PARTYS OWN NEGLIGENCE, GROSS NEGLIGENCE, OR WILLFUL MISCONDUCT. 13.5.5 Royalties. As between Customer on the one hand and Transporter on the other hand, Customer has the sole and exclusive obligation and liability for and shall make payment to all Persons due any proceeds derived from the Gas delivered under a Service Agreement, including royalties, overriding royalties, and similar interests, in accordance with the provisions of the leases or agreements creating those rights to proceeds. In no event will Transporter have any obligation to those Persons due any of those proceeds of production attributable to the Gas delivered under any Service Agreement. Customer hereby agrees to indemnify, defend, and hold harmless Transporter from and against any and all Losses arising out of or related to the proceeds of production attributable to the Gas delivered under any Service Agreement and all Losses arising from the nonpayment, mispayment, or wrongful calculation of payments made by in accordance with this Section 13.5.5. 13.5.6 Taxes. Customer shall pay and be responsible for all Taxes levied against or with respect to Gas delivered or services provided under the Service Agreement. Under no circumstances will Transporter be liable for such Taxes, unless designated to remit those Taxes on behalf of Customer by any duly constituted jurisdictional agency having authority to impose such obligations on Transporter, in which event Customer shall reimburse Transporter for the amount of such Taxes remitted on Customers behalf upon receipt of an invoice, with corresponding documentation from Transporter setting forth such payments. Transporter shall pay and be responsible for all ad valorem Taxes assessed against the Pipeline System or real property relating thereto. Any provision of this SOC to the contrary notwithstanding, each Party shall remain responsible for its own income, margin, franchise, business license, or other Taxes measured by or levied on capital, net income, net margin, capital gain, or imposed on such Party for doing business. Each Party (Tax Indemnifying Party) hereby agrees to indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the other Party from and against any and all Taxes allocable to the Tax Indemnifying Party under this Agreement and all Losses arising from the nonpayment, mispayment, or wrongful calculation of payments made by in accordance with this Section 13.5.6. 13.6 FORCE MAJEURE 13.6.1 Effect of Force Majeure. If either Customer on the one hand or Transporter on the other hand is rendered unable, wholly or in part, by Force Majeure (as defined below), to carry out its obligations under the SOC and any applicable Service Agreement other than the obligation to make payment of amounts due hereunder, then, on such Partys giving notice and reasonably full particulars of such Force Majeure in writing or facsimile or by email to the other Party within a reasonable time after the occurrence of the cause relied on, the obligations of the Party giving such notice, so far as they are affected by such Force Majeure, are suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused, but for no longer period, but the Party claiming Force Majeure shall, so far as possible, remedy such cause with all reasonable dispatch. However, the settlement of strikes or lockouts is entirely within the discretion of the Party having the difficulty and the above requirement that any Force Majeure must be remedied with all reasonable dispatch does not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of the opposing Party when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the Party having the difficulty. 13.6.2 Definition of Force Majeure. The term Force Majeure as employed herein means: acts of God; strikes, lockouts, or other industrial disturbances; acts of the public enemy; wars; blockades; insurrections; sabotage; riots; epidemics; landslides; lightning; freezing of lines of pipe or other equipment; earthquakes; fires; storms; floods; washouts; arrests and restraints of the government, either federal or state, civil or military; civil disturbances; explosions; breakage; breakdown or accident to machinery, equipment, or lines of pipe; and any other causes, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of Customer on the one hand, or Transporter, on the other hand, to the extent such is claiming suspension, and which by the exercise of commercially reasonable efforts such Party is unable, wholly or in part, to prevent or overcome. Such term likewise includes (1) in those instances where either Party is required to obtain servitudes, right-of-way grants, permits, or licenses to enable such Party to fulfill its obligations hereunder, the inability of such Party to acquire, or the delays on the part of such Party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of commercially reasonable efforts, such servitudes, right-of-way grants, or licenses, and (2) in those instances where either Party is required to furnish materials and supplies for the purpose of constructing or maintaining facilities or is required to secure permits or permission from any Governmental Authority to enable such Party to fulfill its obligations hereunder, the inability of such Party to acquire or the delays on the part of such Party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of commercially reasonable efforts, such materials and supplies, permits, and permissions. 13.6.3 Exclusions. Force Majeure does not include changes in market conditions or changes in demand for natural gas. Neither Party is entitled to the benefit of the provision of Force Majeure to the extent performance is affected by any or all of the following circumstances: (i) the Party claiming excuse failing to remedy the condition and to resume the performance of its covenants or obligations with reasonable dispatch; (ii) economic hardship, to include Customers ability to sell its Gas at a higher or more advantageous price to a market not requiring the gas management services contracted for herein; or (iii) the loss of Customers market or Customers inability to use or resell Gas received and delivered hereunder. 13.6.4 Inspection. With the exception of the obligations to make payments due hereunder, either Customer or Transporter may partially or entirely interrupt its performance hereunder for the purpose of Transporter making necessary or desirable inspections, alterations, or repairs, which are described as a maintenance event, but only for such time as may be reasonable and unavoidable; and the Party requiring such relief shall give to the other Party no less than thirty (30) Days notice of its intention to suspend its performance hereunder, except in cases of emergency where such notice is impracticable, and shall endeavor to arrange such interruption so as to inconvenience the other Party as little as possible. If a Force Majeure or maintenance event occurs, then the quantities to be delivered and/or received at the Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s) must be balanced with the nominated quantities. 13.7 WAIVER OF BREACHES, DEFAULTS, OR RIGHTS No waiver by either Party of any one or more breaches, defaults, or rights under any provisions of the SOC or any applicable Service Agreement operates, or is to be construed, as a waiver of any other breaches, defaults, or rights, whether of a like or of a different character. By providing written notice to the other Party, either Party may assert any right not previously asserted hereunder or thereunder or may assert its right to object to a default not previously protested. Transporter reserves the right to vary its operations from the SOC from time to time (consistent with Transporters obligation to act in a manner that is not unduly discriminatory), and the Parties agree that if it does so it will not be deemed to have waived its right subsequently to enforce the provisions of the SOC. Variances from the terms of the SOC or any applicable Service Agreement are not be considered to amend or alter the construction or interpretation of such Service Agreement and SOC. Except as specifically provided herein or in the Service Agreement, in the event of any Dispute under the SOC or any applicable Service Agreement, the Parties shall, notwithstanding the pendency of such Dispute, diligently proceed with the performance of such Service Agreement without prejudice to the rights of either Party. 13.8 REMEDY FOR BREACH Except as otherwise specifically provided herein, if either Party breaches a material warranty or representation or fails to perform any of the material covenants or obligations imposed upon it in the SOC or any applicable Service Agreement (except where such failure is excused under the SOC), then the other Party may, at its option (without waiving any other remedy for breach hereof), by notice in writing specifying the default that has occurred, indicate such Partys intention to terminate such Service Agreement by reason thereof. The Party in default will have thirty (30) Days from receipt of such notice to remedy such material default, and upon failure to do so, the non-defaulting Party may elect to immediately terminate such Service Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Customers failure to pay Transporter within a period of ten (10) business Days following Customers receipt of written notice from Transporter advising of such failure to make payment in full within the time specified previously herein, will be a default that gives Transporter the right to immediately terminate such Service Agreement, unless such failure to pay such amounts is the result of a good faith dispute between the Parties regarding such amounts and Customer timely pays all amounts not in dispute. Such termination will be an additional remedy and will not: (a) prejudice the right of the Party not in default to collect any amounts due it for any damage or loss suffered by it, or (b) waive any other remedy to which the Party not in default may be entitled for breach of the SOC or any applicable Service Agreement. 13.9 CREDITWORTHINESS 13.9.1 Transporters agreement to execute a Service Agreement or to engage in a specific transaction under a Service Agreement is contingent upon a satisfactory appraisal of a potential Customers credit by Transporter. To enable Transporter to conduct such credit appraisal, the potential Customer or its guarantor must submit to Transporter the information set forth in Section 13.9.2 below, and such other financial information reasonably requested by Transporter (including bank references and names of Persons with whom Customer has recently transacted business); provided, however, that Transporters receipt of such material will not be deemed acceptance of the request for a Service Agreement. Transporter will apply consistent evaluation practices on a non-discriminatory basis to determine creditworthiness. 13.9.2 Prior to execution of the Service Agreement and throughout the Term of the Service Agreement, upon Transporters request, potential Customer or Customer, as applicable, shall promptly provide its, its parent entitys, or its guarantors, as applicable, annual audited financial statements and quarterly unaudited financial statements prepared in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles; provided that such requirement shall be deemed satisfied if such financial statements are publicly available. 13.9.3 If Transporter has reasonable grounds for insecurity regarding potential Customers or Customers performance (whether or not then due) of any obligation under the SOC or Service Agreement, including but not limited to, the occurrence of a material change in the creditworthiness of Customer or its guarantor, if applicable, then Transporter may demand Adequate Assurance of Performance. If Customer has not provided Adequate Assurance of Performance to Transporter within two (2) business Days of Customers, or its guarantors, if applicable, receipt of such request, then Transporter will have the right to either (i) suspend performance for which it has not already received the agreed upon return consideration or (ii) terminate the Service Agreement upon written notice, in addition to all other remedies available to it under the Service Agreement. Adequate Assurance of Performance means sufficient security in the form, amount, for a term, and from an issuer, all as reasonably acceptable to Transporter, including, but not limited to (i) cash deposit, (ii) payment with an accelerated due date or a more frequent basis than a Monthly billing cycle, (iii) a standby irrevocable letter of credit, (iv) a prepayment, (v) a security interest in an asset acceptable to Transporter for an amount equal to at least three (3) months demand charges under the Service Agreement, for a term reasonably acceptable to Transporter based upon the volumes flowed by Customer under its Service Agreement in the immediately preceding three (3) Months, or (vi) payment guaranty that satisfies at least two of the following: (A) rated at least Baa3 by Moodys Investors Service, Inc. or its successor with stable outlook; (B) rated at least BBB- by Fitch Ratings Inc. or its successor with stable outlook; and (C) rated at least BBB- by Standard & Poors or its successor with stable outlook. Customer hereby grants to Transporter a continuing first priority security interest in, lien on, and right of setoff against all Adequate Assurance of Performance in the form of cash transferred by Customer to Transporter pursuant to this Section 13.9.3. Upon the return by Transporter to Customer of such Adequate Assurance of Performance, the security interest and lien granted hereunder on that Adequate Assurance of Performance will be released automatically and, to the extent possible, without any further action by either Party. 13.9.4 Transporter will not be required to perform or continue to perform the Services in the event: (i) Customer has voluntarily filed for bankruptcy protection under any chapter of the Bankruptcy Code; (ii) Customer is the subject of an involuntary petition of bankruptcy under any chapter of the Bankruptcy Code, and such involuntary petition has not been settled or otherwise dismissed within sixty (60) Days of such filing; or (iii) Customer otherwise becomes insolvent, whether by an inability to meet its debts as they come due in the ordinary course of business or because its liabilities exceed its assets on a balance sheet test; and/or however such insolvency may otherwise be evidenced. 13.9.5 Should Customer fail to provide Adequate Assurance of Performance within two (2) business Days after receipt of written demand for such assurance, then Transporter shall have the right to suspend performance under this Agreement until such time as Customer furnishes Adequate Assurance of Performance. If such assurance is not provided by Customer within ten (10) Days from written demand, Transporter may terminate the Service Agreement in addition to having any and all other remedies available hereunder.
